column13: A pivotable safety gate having a pair of spaced apart parallel support frames which each have a distal end and a proximal end. The gates prevent accidents and improper entry into areas which should be off limits to passage.

column12: Ceiling board lift
column13: A ceiling board lift comprises two lifting systems 1, 5, an adjustable angle arm 11 and an interconnecting crossbar 8. The first lifting system may include a compression spring 1, a fixed tube 2, a piston tube 4 and a releasable tube clamp 3. The second lifting system 5 may be a friction lifter with a crimp handle or lever and a rod 6. The lift may also include a moveable platform base 7 with wheels. In use the adjustable angle arm 11 may be positioned in a vertical position for loading with a board and then moved to a horizontal position and locked in placed. The tube clamp 3 would then be released slowly taking the board just short of the ceiling. When in position the friction lifter 5 would be crimped until the board was firm to the ceiling and ready to fix. After fixing, a quick release button is pressed to release the pressure and the crossbar 8 could be pulled downwards to compress the spring 1 and then locked with tube clamp 3.

column12: CONTRACEPTIVE HOOD.
column13: Préservatif masculin (10) fixé de manière adhésive au pénis (20), le préservatif (10) étant enroulé (13) sur lui-même et son intérieur étant exempt d'adhésif (15) jusqu'à ce qu'il soit déroulé. Dans un mode préféré de réalisation, le préservatif (50) se compose d'une gaine mince (52) qui sert de dispositif contraceptif et d'un organe cylindrique externe (51) qui est à l'origine enroulé (58) avec la gaine mince (52). L'organe cylindrique externe (51) possède un adhésif (60) sur une partie de sa paroi externe, l'adhésif étant transféré sur la surface interne de la gaine (52) lorsque le préservatif (50) est déroulé sur le pénis (70). A l'origine, l'adhésif (60) est disposé sur la surface externe de l'organe cylindrique externe (51) séparé de la surface externe par un agent de libération (61). Lorsque la gaine (52) est enroulée, l'adhésif (60) sur la surface externe de l'organe cylindrique (51) entre en contact avec la surface interne des spires adjacentes de la gaine (52). Lorsque la gaine (52) est déroulée sur le pénis (70), la couche adhésive (60) adhère et est transférée sur la surface internede la gaine (52) de manière à provoquer l'adhésion de la gaine (52) sur le gland du pénis (70). L'organe externe (51) peut alors être enlevé laissant uniquement la gaine interne mince (52) sur le pénis (70). Une partie en saillie (56) est prévue sur l'organe externe (51) de manière à permettre de saisir l'organe externe (51) pou l'enlever. Le préservatif (10, 50) peut être relativement court de manière à s'étendre uniquement légèrement au-delà du gland du pénis (20). Même lorsque le préservatif (10, 50) est relativement court, il est retenu en position par l'adhésif (15). Le préservatif (82) peut éventuellement s'étendre sur pratiquement toute la longueur du pénis. Dans ce cas également l'adhésif (90) permet de maintenir le préservatif (82) en place.

column12: Two=part rolled-up contraceptive sheath
column13: The cylindrical sheath has a part (50) conically shaped outer section (51) with an air hole (56) at its pointed end and an inner part (52) which is similar to a conventional condom. The outer section (51) is made from a relatively thick material of 0.38-0.63mm thickness and has a principal section (57) which is rolled up with the flange section (54) of the inner part (52) by means of a ring (58). The outer section (51) is provided with a removable layer and an adhesive material so that when the condom is unrolled, the adhesive is transferred to the inner surface of the condom so that it sticks to the surface of the penis. When fully unrolled, the outer section (51) is removed. The air hole (56) prevents a vacuum being formed.

column12: CONTRACEPTIVE HOOD
column13: A male contraceptive hood (10) which is adhesively secured to the penis (20) the hood (10) being initially rolled (13) up and the interior of the hood (10) being free of adhesive (15) until it is unrolled. In a preferred form, the hood (50) has a thin sheath (52) which serves as the contraceptive device and an outer cylindrical member (51) which is initially rolled (58) together with the thin sheath (52). The outer cylindrical member (51) has an adhesive (60) on a portion of its outer wall, which is transferred to the inner surface of the sheath (52) as the hood (50) is unrolled onto a penis (70). Initially, the adhesive (60) is disposed on the outer surface of the outer cylindrical member (51) being separated from the outer surface by a release agent (61). When the sheath (52) is rolled up, the adhesive (60) on the outer surface of the cylindrical member (51) comes into contact with the inner surface of adjacent turns of the sheath (52). As the sheath (52) is unrolled onto the penis (70), the adhesive layer (60) adheres to and is transferred to the inner surface of the sheath (52) so as to cause the sheath (52) to adhere to the head of the penis (70). The outer member (51) can then be removed leaving only the thin inner sheath (52) on the penis (70). A projecting portion (56) is provided on the outer member (51) for grasping the outer member (51) to remove it. The contraceptive hood (10, 50) may be relatively short so as to extend only slightly beyond the head of the penis (20). Even though the hood (10, 50) is relatively short it is retained in position by the adhesive (15). Or the hood (82) may extend over substantially the entire length of the penile shaft. Again, the adhesive (90) is effective in retaining the hood (82) in place.

column12: CONTRACEPTIVE HOOD
column13: A male contraceptive hood which is adhesively secured to the penis, the hood being initially rolled up and the interior of the hood having a layer of adhesive (85) thereon when it is unrolled. The hood has a thin sheath (82) which serves as the contraceptive device and an outer cylindrical member (81) which is initially rolled together with the thin sheath. The outer cylindrical member has a lubricant (92) on its inner surface. After the unit (81) is unrolled onto a penis, the outer member can then be removed leaving only the thin inner sheath (82) on the penis. Some of the lubricant remains on the outer surface on the sheath to facilitate intercourse. A projecting portion (56) is provided on the outer member for grasping the outer member to remove it. The contraceptive hood may be either relatively short (Figures 1 through 10) so as to extend only slightly beyond the head of the penis, or sufficiently long (Figures 12 through 18) to extend over substantially the entire length of the penile shaft.

column12: COMPUTER-IMPLEMENTED METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR TESTING A MODEL
column13: A computer-implemented method for testing a model indicating a parametric relationship between a plurality of channels of multivariate data, the method comprising: obtaining a real dataset of observed multivariate data comprising the plurality of channels; generating a control dataset of multivariate data comprising the plurality of channels, the control dataset being generated based on the model; for each of a plurality of sample subsets from the real dataset and the control dataset, calculating a p-value for the model; and determining whether (1) a distribution difference characteristic of a distribution of the obtained p- values for sample subsets of the real dataset and a distribution of the obtained p-values for sample subsets of the control dataset falls within a second predetermined significance range, and, if condition (1) is met, determining that the model is accurate.
column15: CONWAY JAMES;;BRAGARD QUENTIN

column12: BONE MILL ASSEMBLY FOR USE WITH CORTICAL AND CANCELLOUS BONE
column13: A bone mill assembly provides a drive motor with a reducer. The drive motor is connected to a non-rotating coupler which is connected to a main drive cutting head. A mill housing consists of a manual feed chute or a pneumatic feed chute that shuttles the bone stock onto the main drive cutting head of the mill. The bone stock is ground to a smaller particle size and then shuttled by rotation onto a straight secondary blade. This chops the particle size even smaller and then is sized by an internal window sieve. If the particle size is small enough, the bone particulate passes through the sieve into a collection pan. If the particle size is too large, it will then be rotated back up within the housing to be processed again by the main cutting head. Different sizes of the main cutting head are used for customer specific applications.

column12: COMPUTER-IMPLEMENTED METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR TESTING A MODEL
column13: A computer-implemented method for testing a model indicating a parametric relationship between a plurality of channels of multivariate data, the method comprising: obtaining a real dataset of observed multivariate data comprising the plurality of channels; generating a control dataset of multivariate data comprising the plurality of channels, the control dataset being generated based on the model; for each of a plurality of sample subsets from the real dataset and the control dataset, calculating a p-value for the model; and determining whether (1) a distribution difference characteristic of a distribution of the obtained p-values for sample subsets of the real dataset and a distribution of the obtained p-values for sample subsets of the control dataset falls within a second predetermined significance range, and, if condition (1) is met, determining that the model is accurate.

column12: Integrally-formed foldable container and method
column13: The present invention relates to a method of manufacturing an integrally-formed foldable container (100, figure 1) by injection moulding the container in a partially assembled configuration. The container has panels 110, 120, 130, 140, 150, 160, 170 joined by living hinges, and some adjacent panels 110, 120, 130, 140, 150 are joined by tabs 180, 185, 190, 195. The container is collapsible to a substantially flat collapsed configuration (figure 7) by collectively rearranging the panels. The tabs 180, 185, 190, 195 may be joined to the side panels 120, 130 by a living hinge 189, 199 or may be attachable to form the assembled configuration (figure 12). Living hinges 182, 187, 192, 197 may extend along the entire end panel 140, 150 edge or only part of it. The container may comprise a top panel 160 with a closure means comprising a flap 170 provided with push-fit features configured to engage and disengage with a panel 120 (or 320, figure 10). The container may be formed of polypropylene plastic.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN OR RELATING TO FLEXIBLE HOSES
column13: 1,249,566. Hose. NORMALAIR-GARRETT Ltd. 6 Feb., 1970 [10 Feb., 1969], No. 7041/69. Heading F2P. A hose has an inside ply of flexible, inextensible material 22 and an impermeable outer ply 17 separated by a layer of foam 15, there being a flexible crushproof inner support 14 in the bore of the hose and end fittings 11, 12 attached to the inner ply 22 and having the outer ply 17 partially extending over them. As shown, the tube has an irregularly corrugated surface and the inner support 14 is a helical coil in the bore of the hose. Alternatively a flexible perforated tube also in the bore of the tube may be used. The foam 15 can be open or closed cells of polyurethane, the inner ply 22 of polyester fibre and the outer ply of a knitted polyester fibre coated with silicone rubber. In a method of manufacturing such a hose, Figs. 2-6B (not shown), the inner ply 22 is made integrally with the end fitting 12 to give assembly 16, a fabric cuff is fitted to one end of the inner support 14, which is then placed inside the inner ply 22 with the end fitting adjacent to the cuff, the second end fitting is secured to the inner ply 22 and the layers of foam 15 and outer ply 17 fitted, the latter being secured to the end fittings by heat and pressure. In one embodiment the spring 14 has one close coiled end and a cuff of polyester fibre 20 is secured to it using a diluted elastomeric adhesive by wrapping it over the coil when mounted on a mandrel 21. The end fitting 12 is made integrally with the inner ply 22 by sandwiching one end of the latter between layers of rubber 24, 25 built up on a pattern 23, the ribbon and inner ply's end are then subjected to heat and pressure by placing a mould around the covered pattern 23. The spring 14 with the cuff 20 is then inserted inside the inner ply 22 with the cuff 20 and end fitting 12 adjacent. End fitting 11 is then fitted to both the spring 14 and inner ply 22. A layer of polyurethane foam is wrapped to form a tube and joined to the ends of the inner ply by adhesive. The outer ply may be formed by skelping or convolutely winding a sheet of silicone rubber coated polyester fibre which is placed over the remainder of the hose by drawing the latter through it and sticking the outer ply 17 to the end fittings 11, 12.

column13: A tufted nonwoven high loft fabric is made by using paper making techniques with an apertured fibre collecting plate. The plate presents entanglement between adjacent tufts prior to removal of the fabric from the plate. The tufted non-woven fabric has inwardly turned spirally consolidated and entangled individual tuft head portions together with aligned and untwisted root portions. The letter interconnect the tuft head portions to the undisturbed main body of the web material. column12: Process of forming wet laid tufted nonwoven fibrous web and tufted product
column13: A tufted nonwoven web material exhibiting high loft, bulk and absorbency is made by a papermaking technique using an apertured, plate-like, fiber-collecting element having a structure appropriate to preventing entanglement between adjacent tufts prior to removal from the element. The apertured element is adapted not only to form the tufted nonwoven fibrous web but also to permit consolidation of individual tufts and facilitate the formation of tufted webs from 100 percent wood pulp. Additionally, webs having tufts on both planar surfaces also can be formed by this technique.

column12: PROCEDIMIENTO MEJORADO PARA PRODUCIR UN MATERIAL DE BANDA FRIBROSO, TENDIDO CON AGUA, NO TEJIDO, MECHOSO, Y PRODUCTO RESULTANTE
column13: La presente invención se refiere a un procedimiento mejorado para producir un material de banda fibroso, tendido con agua, no tejido, mechoso, caracterizado proque comprende los pasos de proveer un elemento recolector de fibras, de forma de placa, que tiene una superficie recolectora de fibras lisa y una multitud de aberturas que se extienden de dicha superficie contínuamente a través del elemento, cada una de las aberturas teniendo una porción de labio en dicha superficie y una configuración generalmente tubular a través del elemento, proveer una disperción fluída de fibras seleccionadas del grupo que consiste de fibras naturales y artificiales y mezclas de las mismas, adecuadas para ser dispersadas en un medio acuoso de una viscosidad de, por lo menos, aproximadamente 0.01 por ciento en peso, y depositar las fibras de la dispersión sobre el elemento-recolector de fibras para promover el flujo laminar del medio acuoso de dispersión de fibras a través de las aberturas tubulares en el elemento de forma de placa, y una formar de tal manera un material de banda fibroso, no tejido, mechoso sobre el elemento, la banda teniendo mechones integrales formados de faces de fibras individuales estrechamente asociadas que se extienden sobre la porción de labio y dentro de las aberturas en el elemento.

column12: ORGANIZED HEALTHCARE FRAUD DETECTION
column13: A fraud detection system receives information that identifies healthcare claims associated with providers and beneficiaries, and determines, based on the healthcare claims, first fraud sets associated with postulated classes of fraud. The fraud detection system determines, based on the healthcare claims, second fraud sets using one or more data mining techniques, and calculates probabilities that the first fraud sets and the second fraud sets are similar to no fraud observations. The fraud detection system ranks the first fraud sets and the second fraud sets based on the calculated probabilities, and outputs a ranked list of suspected fraud cases, associated with the healthcare claims, based on the ranking of the first fraud sets and the second fraud sets.

column12: SCALABLE LIQUID COOLING SYSTEM WITH MODULAR RADIATORS
column13: A scalable and modular cooling system is disclosed. The cooling system includes an air plenum with a plurality of expansion slots. Each expansion slot is configured to receive a modularly configured fluid-to-air heat exchanger, such as a radiator. The air plenum also include one or more air movers for blowing air through the expansion slots, and therefore through any radiators fitted within the expansion slots. For those expansion slots that are not used, a blanking plate is fitted to each unused expansion slot. Each blanking plate is modularly configured in a manner similar to the modularly configured radiators. In this manner, air bypass is substantially prevented. Each radiator is part of an independent cooling loop, used directly or indirectly to cool heat generating devices.

column12: Antimicrobial compositions and eyewear
column13: A composition comprises amorphous calcium phosphate glass particles dispersed in a polymer comprising cellulose acetate propionate, polycarbonate, or acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene (ABS), wherein the glass particles contain silver oxide and/or silver sulfadiazine. Preferably, the composition comprises 1500-4000 ppm silver oxide and/or silver sulfadiazine. The molecular weights of cellulose acetate propionate, polycarbonate, and ABS may be 1000-3000, 150-400, and 100-350 g/mol, respectively. Another polymer may be included, especially an elastomer like ethylene-vinyl acetate. The composition is typically antimicrobial. Articles comprising the composition are also disclosed, which may be spectacle cases comprising ABS or eyewear, such as spectacles, sunglasses, or safety glasses, having frames comprising cellulose acetate propionate or polycarbonate. A method of manufacturing such articles comprises dispersing the glass particles containing silver oxide and/or silver sulfadiazine into a carrier to form a dispersion, blending the dispersion into the polymer to form a blend, and shaping the blend, e.g. by injection moulding.

column12: Sheet Discharge Assembly for a Printer
column13: A printer for printing individual sheets from a continuous feed roll includes a housing configured for receipt of a feed roll of sheet material, and a print mechanism disposed within the housing, whereby the sheet material is conveyed within the housing to print mechanism. A sheet separating device is disposed within the housing downstream of the print mechanism to separate the sheet material into individual printed sheets. A discharge assembly is disposed downstream of the sheet separating device and defines a gap through which the sheet material is advanced. At least one protruding member is disposed in the gap at a position so as to contact and deflect the sheet material and to impart a curved transverse profile to a trailing edge of a first individual sheet held in the gap. In this manner, a leading edge of a subsequent sheet bisects the curved trailing edge of the first sheet and pushes the first sheet out of the gap as the second sheet is advanced through the print mechanism.

The roadway guardrail 100 is operatively coupled to the one or more roadway guardrail posts 200 by the one or more fasteners 320, and each of the one or more reinforcing members is located between the roadway guardrail 100 and a respective one of the one or more roadway guardrail posts 200 such that the first surface of the reinforcing member engages the contact surface of the roadway guardrail post and the second surface of the reinforcing member engages a surface of the roadway guardrail 100, and a portion of each slot 230 aligns with one of the one or more mounting apertures at a desired height of the roadway guardrail. Upon a vehicle impact with the roadway guardrail 100 the one or more fasteners, the one or more reinforcing members, and the roadway guardrail 100 slide upwards with respect to the one or more guardrail posts 200, such that the one or more reinforcing members slide upwards with respect to the contact surfaces of the one or more roadway guardrail posts 200 along at least one of the one or more slots. The upward movement of the one or more fasteners, the one or more reinforcing members, and the roadway guardrail 100 is inhibited when at least one of the one or more fasteners contacts an end of the at least one of the one or more slots, such that energy of the collision is dissipated as the one or more reinforcing members slide with respect to the contact surfaces of the one or more roadway guardrail posts 200 and the at least one of the one or more fasteners contacts the end of the at least one of the one or more slots.

column12: Compactor-feeder for solid waste incinerator
column13: Converging upper and lower conveyors transport loose waste from a receiving hopper toward an incinerator combustion chamber entrance at an adjustably predetermined normal rate, cooperating to compact the waste into a continuous plug and to force the plug through a confining passageway extending from the conveyors to the incinerator entrance, thereby feeding the waste plug to the burning firebed in the combustion chamber at a steady rate for causing waste combustion therein at a generally steady rate while sealing the entrance thereto against incoming air and outgoing heat or fire. The upper conveyor is movable and selectively biased downwardly for waste compaction when the conveyors transport a predetermined normal quantity of waste; but the bias is removed upon transport of an abnormal quantity, and a fire door at the entrance and a firestop spaced therefrom in the passageway are closed on whatever waste may be thereunder for further local compression thereof while the conveyors are reversed to travel at a higher rate to clear themselves if they are transporting a greater than normal quantity and speeded up to travel at the higher rate in feeding direction if transporting a lesser than normal quantity. Transport toward the incinerator is resumed upon clearing, but at the higher rate. The firestop opens, and, thereafter the fire door opens and the normal transport rate resumes upon again transporting a normal quantity of waste. The fire door and firestop also close if the conveyors are shut down, and serve when closed to further seal off the incoming waste from the heat and fire in the incinerator.

column12: Improvements in and connected with Apparatus for Intensifying and Reducing Fluid Pressure.
column13: 5374. Preston, E. J., and Conway, F. L. March 21. Intensifiers.-Relates to means for intensifying or reducing fluid pressure, one form for intensifying being shown in sectional elevation in Fig. 1. The low-pressure cylinder A has a ram C, of larger effective area than the ram D of the highpressure cylinder B. When fluid under slight pressure is allowed to flow from the main T through the pipe Q to the cylinder C, the rams are moved upwards, and fluid under high pressure passes from the cylinder B through the pipe V. The action is made automatic by providing the end of the ram D with a lug E adapted to operate the arms F, W of a counterpoised tripping-device G connected to a several-way cock H. In the position shown, fluid flows from the main 1 through the cock H and pipe K to the underside of the piston N, and the fluid above the piston exhausts through the pipe L and cock H. The piston thus holds the valve 0 so that fluid under slight pressure flows from the main T into the cylinder A, and under high pressure from the cylinder B through the pipe V, the high-pressure fluid being prevented by a non-return valve U from flowing through the pipe into the valvechest. When the position of the cock H is altered by the movement of the tripping-devices, the valve 0 is moved down, and fluid flows from the cylinder A through the pipe Q into the exhaust S. The high-pressure fluid may help the downward motion of the ram by flowing back through the pipe V, or this backward flow may be prevented by a valve in the pipe V, in which case fluid from the main T raises the valve U and flows into the cylinder B. In modifications, the tripping-device may operate directly the valve 0, and, where the apparatus is employed for reducing-pressure, the pipe V leads from the low-pressure cylinder A, the valve U is dispensed with, and the valve 0 is set to allow the fluid in the cylinder B to compress the fluid in the cylinder A.

column12: SCALABLE LIQUID COOLING SYSTEM WITH MODULAR RADIATORS
column13: A scalable and modular cooling system is disclosed. The cooling system includes an air plenum with a plurality of expansion slots. Each expansion slot is configured to receive a modularly configured fluid-to-air heat exchanger, such as a radiator. The air plenum also include one or more air movers for blowing air through the expansion slots, and therefore through any radiators fitted within the expansion slots. For those expansion slots that are not used, a blanking plate is fitted to each unused expansion slot. Each blanking plate is modularly configured in a manner similar to the modularly configured radiators. In this manner, air bypass is substantially prevented. Each radiator is part of an independent cooling loop, used directly or indirectly to cool heat generating devices.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR CONTROLLING HOME APPLIANCES
column13: A hand-held remote control which can be configured to communicate command codes to one or more home appliances of different makes, models, and manufacturers and a relay unit that can communicate with the remote control. The relay unit has a button that corresponds to a key on the remote control. When the button on the relay unit is activated, the relay unit signals the remote control. In response to the receipt of the signal indicating activation of the button or in response to activation of the key on the remote control, the remote control communicates to one or more of the home appliances those command codes that have been mapped to the key. Command codes are communicated to the home appliances using native communication protocols.
column15: CONWAY JAMES N;;HAYES PATRICK H

column12: Composite ceramic composition and method of forming same
column13: A composite ceramic composition including a boron carbide phase and a method of forming the same. The composite ceramic composition includes a tungsten boride phase, a transition metal boride phase. The composite ceramic composition may also include a carbon disposed in solid solution with at least the tungsten boride phase and the transition metal boride phase. The transition metal boride phase may include a boride of at least one metal chosen from Cr, Nb, and Zr.

column12: Electric shower
column13: An electric shower (100, Fig.1) comprises an integrated Ohmic water heater 200. The electric shower may provide a single water flow path passing through the water heater from an inlet 216 to an outlet 218, the inlet being connected to a water supply pipe and the outlet being connected to a showerhead (114, Fig.1). The water heater may comprise a plurality of electrode plates 206. The water may flow in a serpentine path around the electrode plates. The electric shower may comprise an electronic controller (210, Fig.3) to control the water heater, and a flow rate sensor located upstream of the water heater to provide flow data to the electronic controller to adjust control of the water heater. The electronic controller may control the water heater based on one or more of user input, temperature data and flow rate data. The electric shower may provide a “pause” function such that a water flow therefrom can be stopped and re-started without providing over-heated water. A method of providing heated water from an electric shower comprises supplying unheated water to an electric shower, heating the water within the electric shower using Ohmic heating, and providing the heated water to a showerhead.

column12: Sheet discharge assembly for a printer
column13: A printer for printing individual sheets from a continuous feed roll includes a housing configured for receipt of a feed roll of sheet material, and a print mechanism disposed within the housing, whereby the sheet material is conveyed within the housing to print mechanism. A sheet separating device is disposed within the housing downstream of the print mechanism to separate the sheet material into individual printed sheets. A discharge assembly is disposed downstream of the sheet separating device and defines a gap through which the sheet material is advanced. At least one protruding member is disposed in the gap at a position so as to contact and deflect the sheet material and to impart a curved transverse profile to a trailing edge of a first individual sheet held in the gap. In this manner, a leading edge of a subsequent sheet bisects the curved trailing edge of the first sheet and pushes the first sheet out of the gap as the second sheet is advanced through the print mechanism.

column12: Anitmicrobial compositions and eyewear
column13: A polymer composition comprises nanoparticles dispersed in cellulose acetate propionate, polycarbonate, or acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene, wherein the nanoparticles comprise silver orthophosphate. Preferably, the nanoparticles also contain silver oxide and/or silver sulphadiazine and have a particle size of 1-1000 nm, especially 1-100 nm. The composition may comprise a further polymer, such as a polyethylene-vinyl acetate elastomer. An article, such as a spectacles case, spectacles, sunglasses, safety glasses, or other optical equipment, comprising the composition is also disclosed. The article will typically have antimicrobial properties. In another aspect, a method of manufacturing an article comprises the steps of (i) dispersing silver orthophosphate nanoparticles into a carrier to form a dispersion, (ii) blending the dispersion into cellulose acetate propionate, polycarbonate, or acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene polymer to form a blend, and (iii) shaping the blend to produce the article. The shaping step may comprise injection moulding.

column12: AN APPARATUS, METHOD AND COMPUTER PROGRAM PRODUCT FOR DETERMINING A LEVEL OF RISK
column13: An apparatus for determining a level of risk that a future transfer will exceed a level of reserve is provided by the present disclosure, the apparatus comprising circuitry configured to: obtain data of transfers between financial institutions which have occurred at a number of instances of time, the data including transfer amounts; apply a predictive model to the data to obtain a prediction of the transfer amount at each instance of time; determine a maximum residual between the prediction of the transfer amount and the transfer amount at each instance of time; model the maximum residual for each instance of time using a generalised extreme value distribution to obtain a distribution function; and determine the level of risk that a future transfer between financial institutions will exceed the level of reserve based on the distribution function which has been obtained.

column13: A system which can be configured to communicate command codes to one or more home appliances which includes a keypad and a relay unit. At least one key on the keypad is associated with at least one command code from a plurality of command codes stored in a memory. The system determines if the at least one key on the keypad has been activated or if a command signal transmission that identifies the at least one key on the keypad has been received from the relay unit. When it is determined that either the at least one key has been activated or the command signal transmission that identifies the at least one key has been received, the system communicates to the one or more of home appliances the one or more command codes that have been associated to the at least one key on the keypad.

column12: ROADWAY GUARDRAIL SYSTEM
column13: A roadway guardrail system including a rail, a plurality of support posts, and a plurality of fasteners assembly to redirect an impacting vehicle and dissipate a portion of the impacting vehicle's energy. column12: Roadway guardrail system which slides upwards on impact
column13: A roadway guardrail system 50 comprises a support post 200, where the support post 200 comprises a first end disposed at an upper portion of the support post 200, a second end disposed at a lower portion of the support post 200 and a longitudinal axis extending between the first end and the second end, and a rail 100 having a mounting aperture, where the rail 100 is operatively coupled to the support post 200, a fastener 320 coupled to the rail 100, and a reinforcing member 310 located between the rail 100 and the support post 200. The rail 100, the fastener 320 and the reinforcing member 310 are configured to, in response to a collision with the rail 100, move in an upward direction relative to the support post 200 to dissipate energy from the collision. After a predetermined upper movement the support post 200 inhibits the upper movement of the rail 100, the fastener 320, and the reinforcing member 310 to further dissipate energy from the collision.

column12: Production of spun yarns
column13: In the production of bulked, staple fibre yarn, bonded fibre fabrics, woven and knitted fabrics, a travelling tow of continuous cellulose or wholly synthetic thermoplastic filaments is variably modified e.g. by continuously stretching between pairs of conical and/or cylindrical, variable-speed rollers, and/or relaxing and/or heating and cooling, or by chemical treatment, along or across selected successive portions of the tow, in such continous or discontinuous manner that the modification or a part thereof is retained as a latent property in the filaments pending further treatment. The modification is such that the filaments (or parts thereof or fibres cut therefrom into staple length and perhaps crimped) undergo a corresponding variable change of length by shrinkage or extension when subjected to a uniform length-changing treatment e.g. wet or dry heating or chemical treatment of relaxed or tensioned-filaments at the fibre or (single or plied) yarn stage. The difference in modification extends longitudinally of each filament and/or between different filaments. Individual stapled fibres may have a shrinkage characteristic which varies from a maximum at one end to a minimum at the other end. Staple derived from separately prepared tows, p the filaments of which may differ as regards chemical nature, form and/or denier, may be blended and spun into yarn. A bulky fabric comprises polyacrylinitrile fibres bonded with rubber latex and then subjected to a steam treatment to induce differential shrinkage within and/or between the fibres. In apparatus for subjecting viscose filaments to a variable liquid treatment, Fig. 3 (not shown) the tow passes through a bath 19 containing a water-soluble ethylene urea formaldehyde precondensate and a resinifying catalyst such as magnesium or ammonium chloride, thence through driven nip rollers 20 the squeeze pressure between which is varied (by mechanism comprising rotating arm 23, lever 22 and loading spring 21) so as to effect a variable expression of the bath liquid: alternatively or additionally, the resin concentration of the liquid may be varied. The tow then passes through a curing oven 24, water and finish solution baths 25 and 26 and a drier 27. Staple fibre yarn produced from the resultant filaments is immersed in a shrinking agent e.g. aqueous caustic soda solution, and the yarn thus bulked may be stabilized by cross-linkage or the application of a crease-resistant resin. In the stapling apparatus of Fig. 4 (not shown) polyacrylic tow is fed between rollers 35, 36, and 37, 38. Roller 37 is of rubber and roller 38 is surfaced with rubber, carries cutters 39 and rotates eccentrically so that each cut fibre is relaxed in a continuous variable manner from 0-20% from end to end. Steam and cooling air are directed on to the tow by jets 40 and 41. Yarn spun from this staple and heat-treated develops a structure varying from open on the outer surface to compact at the core. In another apparatus, Fig. 5 (not shown) the tow is stapled by a traversing cutter 42 trailing a steam nozzle 43:yarn spun from the staple and heat-treated shows a sharply defined transition from a compact core to a loose surface.

column12: A method of Treating Textile Fibres
column13: 1,174,003. Bulky yarns. LINEN INDUSTRY RESEARCH ASSOCIATION. 16 Jan., 1968 [24 Jan., 1967], No. 3507/67., Headings D1F and D1W. An assembly of textile fibres some at least of which have been produced by highly stretching and then severing continuous filaments into staple fibres having high potential shrinkage receives a heat treatment in which different parts of the assembly are subjected to different temperatures so that the highly stretched fibres have variable shrinkage characteristics and a yarn made from the assembly bulks when subjected to a shrinking process. Different parts of the assembly may be subjected to discrete temperatures-for example, room temperature and a temperature producing maximum shrinkage-or to temperatures varying within a given range. In one embodiment a sliver is passed on a lattice through an air curtain comprised of air of two temperatures mixed by a rotary valve which is rotated by a motor to vary the mixture. In a second embodiment a sliver is laid in a zigzag manner on a perforated conveyor which passes through a hot air box which is divided laterally of the conveyor into a plurality of compartments each having a fan and an electric heater-the heaters having different ratings. In a third embodiment the sliver is drawn through a fluidised bed having a variable temperature. The assembly may be heated in the presence of moisture. The fibres may be polyacrylonitrile, polyester, or modacrylic fibres.

column12: Continuous filament bulked yarns
column13: 1,042,582. Spinning yarns. LINEN INDUSTRY RESEARCH ASSOCIATION. Aug. 27, 1962 [Aug. 26, 1961. Jan. 17, 1962 (2); May 25, 1962], Nos. 13302/66, 13303/66, 13304/66 and 13305/66 Divided out of 1, 042, 581. Headings D1F and DIW. [Also in Division B5] In the production of bulked yarn, drawn, wholly synthetic e.g. polyacrylic, thermoplastic, continuous filaments are simultaneously and variably stretched (as they are produced from a spinneret or subsequently) by passage of a sheet of the filaments through a drawing apparatus comprising two pairs of similarly dimensioned and driven, but oppositely disposed, conical rollers linked by mechanism which repeatedly causes the rollers to separate in turn so that the pairs alternately grip and effect stretching of the filaments. All or most of the filaments are thus stretched by varying amounts along their length (dependent on the speed of the rollers and the frequency of transfer of effective operation from one pair to the other) and also across the sheet. The filaments are twisted into a yarn which is subjected to a uniform heat shrinkage treatment to bulk the yarn as a result of differential shrinkage effects within and between the filaments. The effect may be further varied by changing the twist.

column12: An apparatus, method and computer program product for determining a level of risk
column13: A method and apparatus for determining a level of risk that a future transfer will exceed a level of reserve is provided. The method comprises steps to obtain data S6002 of transfers between financial institutions which have occurred at a number of instances of time, the data including transfer amounts. A predictive model is applied S6004 to the data to obtain a prediction of the transfer amount at each instance of time, and a maximum residual between the prediction of the transfer amount and the transfer amount at each instance of time is determined S6006. The maximum residual for each instance of time is modelled S6008 using a generalised extreme value distribution to obtain a distribution function, and the level of risk that a future transfer between financial institutions will exceed the level of reserve is determined S6010 based on the distribution function which has been obtained.

column12: HOLOGRAPHIC INTERACTIVE RETAIL SYSTEM
column13: Systems and methods herein are directed to a holographic interactive retail system. In particular, various embodiments are described where a holographic image (e.g., Pepper's Ghost Illusion) is used in a retail setting (e.g., storefront window), which, when combined with gesture control, allows people to walk up to the system and search for and buy products. A final purchase can be made through the customer's mobile device or through a self-service kiosk, shipping the product to their house.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN OR RELATING TO THE MANUFACTURE OF YARNS AND STAPLE FIBRE
column13: 1,215,571. Stapling fibres and spinning bulky yarns. LINEN INDUSTRY RESEARCH ASSOCIATION, 20 Dec., 1967 [21 Sept., 1966], No. 42054/66. Headings D1F and D1W. A method of making staple fibre with bulk potential comprises the steps of producing an assembly of filaments having variable shrinkage characteristics, stapling the filaments so that there are present potentially high shrinkage fibres which have a materially greater staple length, e.g. 1 inch greater, than the remaining fibres many of which will have substantially less shrinkability, and passing the staple fibres through a drafting system having a reach which will stretch break the fibres of high potential shrinkage but not the remaining fibres. The fibres are then spun into a yam and subjected to a uniform shrinkage process to cause variable shrinkage of the yam fibres. The assembly of filaments may be a single tow or a blend of two tows.

column12: RADAR SYSTEM FOR DETECTING PROFILES OF OBJECTS, PARTICULARLY IN A VICINITY OF A MACHINE WORK TOOL
column13: An implement for use with an excavator includes a lightweight housing, a first coupling feature, a ground penetrating radar antenna, a controller, a wireless communication circuit and a rotation unit. The lightweight housing has an upper surface, a lower surface and a cavity. The first coupling feature is located on the upper surface and cooperates with a second coupling feature on an excavator arm. The ground penetrating radar antenna is mounted near the lower surface. The controller is mounted within the cavity and provides outgoing signals to the radar antenna, receives incoming signals from the radar antenna and interprets the incoming signals so as to provide implement output information. The wireless communication circuit is mounted within the cavity and transmits the implement output information. The rotation unit is mounted within the cavity and rotates the housing vis-à-vis the excavator arm.

column12: Soporte corporal inflable con pocillos de mano de forma de huesos de perro
column13: Un soporte corporal inflable (13) formado por un par de láminas de plástico unidas conjuntamente que forman entre ellas una cámara presurizable con aire, teniendo las láminas una pluralidad de agujeros alineados que se extienden a su través, estando las láminas unidas conjuntamente alrededor de la circunferencia de cada agujero para permitir que el calor y la humedad del cuerpo fluyan a través de cada agujero, pero impidiendo que el aire fluya desde la cámara al interior de cada agujero, proporcionando así un colchón de aire para soportar una persona posicionada encima que disipa presión, calor y humedad con el fin de impedir la aparición de llagas y úlceras de presión, y teniendo oclusiones unidas a dichas láminas alrededor de la circunferencia de una pluralidad de dichos agujeros sobre los cuales no yacerían el torso, la cabeza y las extremidades de una persona posicionada encima del soporte corporal inflable (13) , ocluyendo tales agujeros y reduciendo cualquier distensión del soporte corporal inflable que rodea los agujeros ocluidos y centrando así el volumen del aire dentro de la cámara presurizada debajo de un persona colocada encima del soporte corporal inflable (13), caracterizado porque: una pluralidad de pocillos de mano alineados (14) de forma de huesos de perro que se extienden a través de las láminas de plástico, estando las láminas unidas conjuntamente alrededor de la circunferencia de cada pocillo de mano (14) de forma de hueso de perro reemplaza a una pluralidad de dichos agujeros ocluidos sobre los que no yacerían el torso, cabeza y extremidades de una persona, con radios grandes en los extremos de los pocillos de mano (14) de forma de huesos de perro que eliminan la creación de puntos de cizalladura y esfuerzo cuando se abren bajo esfuerzos de estiramiento para formar un círculo completo, enfocando así el esfuerzo de estiramiento por igual a lo largo de toda la circunferencia del círculo, proporcionando, por tanto, un pocillo de mano que aguanta una cantidad mayor de fuerza antes de crear fatiga o fallo del material.

column12: PROCEDE CONTINU DE FABRICATION D'UNE DISPERSION UNIFORME DE FIBRES
column13:
La présente invention concerne un procédé de fabrication d'une dispersion uniforme de fibres.

Le procédé est mis en oeuvre par l'utilisation d'une installation comprenant une chambre de dispersion en continu comprenant un certain nombre d'agitateurs rotatifs dans des compartiments créant des zones de pression réduite et de turbulence d'intensité élevée, cette turbulence étant suffisante pour rapidement ouvrir les faisceaux de fibres et disperser les fibres individuelles longues dans le liquide de dispersion.

L'invention permet la fabrication de feuilles continues de fibres avec dispersion uniforme de fibres dans cette feuille continue.

column12: Method for customizing a remote control and related computer server
column13: A customizable and an upgradable remote control (10) is provided which may be customized or upgraded via a Web site (30) or through other remote, and preferably interactive, processes. A database (12) is provided which includes a plurality of functions of a consumer electronic device, such as a T.V. or and DVD player. In one embodiment a database of command codes operable with a hand-held device is maintained. A user is allowed to access the database via a Web site (30). Such an interactive environment may include pay-per-event access, and the like.

column12: A GOLFING PUTTER
column13: This invention relates to a golfing putter and, more particularly, a golfing putter (1) for helping golfers strike a golf ball (17) consistently without inducing backspin on the ball. The golfing putter (1) comprises a head (2) fixed to a shaft (3). The head (2) has a front face (7) for striking the golf ball (17), and an upper face (6) disposed in use towards the golfer. The vertical centre of mass (8) is behind an upper portion of the front face (7) of the head (2). The head (2) has at least in a central portion (35) of the front face (7) an inverted L-shaped cross-section with the top face (6) forming an upper arm (36) of the L-shape and the front face (7) forming the front arm (37) of the L-shape. The front arm (37) is thinner than the top arm (36). The head therefore has a vertical centre of mass (8) behind an upper third of the front face (7) of the head (2) above the impact point with the golf ball (17).

column12: RADAR SYSTEM FOR DETECTING PROFILES OF OBJECTS, PARTICULARLY IN A VICINITY OF A MACHINE WORK TOOL
column13: An implement for use with an excavator includes a lightweight housing, a first coupling feature, a ground penetrating radar antenna, a controller, a wireless communication circuit and a rotation unit. The lightweight housing has an upper surface, a lower surface and a cavity. The first coupling feature is located on the upper surface and cooperates with a second coupling feature on an excavator arm. The ground penetrating radar antenna is mounted near the lower surface. The controller is mounted within the cavity and provides outgoing signals to the radar antenna, receives incoming signals from the radar antenna and interprets the incoming signals so as to provide implement output information. The wireless communication circuit is mounted within the cavity and transmits the implement output information. The rotation unit is mounted within the cavity and rotates the housing vis-a-vis the excavator arm.

column12: Scalable liquid cooling system with modular radiators
column13: A scalable and modular cooling system is disclosed. The cooling system includes an air plenum with a plurality of expansion slots. Each expansion slot is configured to receive a modularly configured fluid-to-air heat exchanger, such as a radiator. The air plenum also include one or more air movers for blowing air through the expansion slots, and therefore through any radiators fitted within the expansion slots. For those expansion slots that are not used, a blanking plate is fitted to each unused expansion slot. Each blanking plate is modularly configured in a manner similar to the modularly configured radiators. In this manner, air bypass is substantially prevented. Each radiator is part of an independent cooling loop, used directly or indirectly to cool heat generating devices.

column12: Roadway guardrail system
column13: A roadway guardrail system including a rail and plurality of support posts assembled such that upon impact from a vehicle the rail moves upwardly with respect to the post. Fasteners may be used in the operative coupling of the rail to the support posts, such that upon impact the fasteners move upwardly with respect to the support posts and the rail moves upwardly along with the fasteners. The guardrail system may further include a reinforcing member that is slidable along the post and operatively coupled to the rail with the fasteners, such that the rail and fasteners slide along with the reinforcing member with respect to the support posts. The reinforcing member may be a spacer of various shapes, a washer, an additional rail section, or other type of member that allows the rail to slide upwardly with respect to the post.

column12: Process for producing a uniform fiber dispersion and machine made light weight glass fiber web material
column13: A process of producing a uniform fiber dispersion involves the use of an in-line dispersing chamber to provide an average fiber dwell time of only about ten minutes and less. The chamber is provided with a plurality of weedless, nonthrusting impellers that generate regions of reduced pressure and flow disruptive turbulence of high intensity, the turbulence being of sufficient intensity to rapidly open fiber bundles and disperse the individual long fibers during said dwell time within said chamber. The process produces a machine-made light weight glass fiber web material of exceptionally uniform fiber distribution. The web is comprised of micron diameter glass fibers having a fiber length of about 1/4 inch or more and a basis weight of about 5-30 grams/square meter. The web material exhibits an isolated multi-fiber defect count of less than 10 per 100 square feet and a visually perceptible overall uniform fiber distribution essentially devoid of "cloud effect" fiber density variations.

column12: FEUILLE CONTINUE DE FIBRES DE VERRE MINCE, FABRIQUEE A LA MACHINE
column13:
La présente invention concerne une feuille continue de fibres de verre, mince fabriquée à la machine présentant une distribution exceptionnellement uniforme de fibres.

La feuille continue comprend des fibres de verre de diamètre de l'ordre du micron possédant une longueur de fibres d'environ 0,63 cm ou davantage et une force de 5-30 g/m**2, cette feuille continue présentant un dénombrement de défauts de faisceaux de fibres isolés inférieur à 10 par 10 m**2 et une distribution des fibres uniforme visuellement perceptible, libre de toute variation de densité de fibres formant des nuages. L'invention est utilisable pour la fabrication de feuilles continues de fibres inorganiques.

Se référer à la figure unique.

column12: A showerhead with means for adding pressurized gas or gases into the water stream
column13: A showerhead in the form of a handset 1 is provided with an internal diffuser 17 operable to inject a gas or a mixture of gases as a stream of fine bubbles into a water stream upstream of a spray head 5 prior to discharge from the handset 1. Adding the gas or mixture of gases to the water stream within the handset 1 has the effect of volumizing the water which increases both the perceived flow rate and spray force without altering the actual flow rate. The handset 1 has particular application to showers employing an instantaneous electric water heater as the source of temperature controlled water. A pump (21 figure 2) may be added to the spray head 5. A later embodiment relates to a method of adding a gas or a mixture of gases to a water stream in a shower.

column12: Processing data structures
column13: A data processing device is provided with processing means, memory means, input means and display means. The memory means storing an operating system, a plurality of applications, user data sorted as data files and at least one database. At least one application configures the device to declare a unique variable corresponding to an entity in a database stored in the memory means and reserve a storage address range of the memory means as a virtual file system for the entity. Upon a user selecting the entity with the input means in a graphical user interface displayed on the display means, the application further configures the device to output any data structures associated with the entity in the database to the display means and upon a user selecting a data structure for association with the entity, the application further configures the device to update the virtual file system with extracting details of the data structure representative of the storage address thereof. The application also further configures and device to displace the data structure to an alternate storage address and output a record of the alternate storage address in the database. <Figure 1>

column12: ROADWAY GUARDRAIL SYSTEM
column13: A roadway guardrail system including a rail and plurality of support posts assembled such that upon impact from a vehicle the rail moves upwardly with respect to the post. Fasteners may be used in the operative coupling of the rail to the support posts, such that upon impact the fasteners move upwardly with respect to the support posts and the rail moves upwardly along with the fasteners. The guardrail system may further include a reinforcing member that is slidable along the post and operatively coupled to the rail with the fasteners, such that the rail and fasteners slide along with the reinforcing member with respect to the support posts. The reinforcing member may be a spacer of various shapes, a washer, an additional rail section, or other type of member that allows the rail to slide upwardly with respect to the post.

column12: CUSTOMIZABLE AND UPGRADABLE DEVICES AND METHODS RELATED THERETO
column13: A customizable and an upgradable remote control is provided which may be customized or upgraded via a Web site or through other remote, and preferably interactive, processes. A database is provided which includes a plurality of functions of a consumer electronic device, such as a T.V. or and DVD player. A user selects among the plurality of functions at least one of the desired functions. In response to the user selection a virtual configuration is created to virtually configure the customized remote control. The virtual configuration may be downloaded to the customizable remote control. Preferably, the customizable remote control is provided with a plurality of preprogrammed standard keys and a plurality of configurable keys. A plurality of customized labels corresponding to the plurality of configurable keys may be provided separately or printed as part of the virtual configuration download process. More generally methods for providing a customized consumer electronic device are disclosed, including a preferred embodiment using a touch screen remote control. In one embodiment a database of command codes operable with a hand-held device is maintained. A user is allowed to access the database via a Web site. The user may then download at least one of the plurality of command codes provided in the selection. The hand-held device may also be utilized in an interactive environment. Such an interactive environment may include pay-per-event access, and the like.

column12: ELECTRONIC BILLBOARD AND VEHICLE TRAFFIC CONTROL COMMUNICATION SYSTEM.
column13: A communication system uses simple microwave transmitters disposed along roadways and in-vehicle mounted receivers to transmit encoded signals to produce location-specific commercial, traffic regulatory, emergency and other information to operators of motor vehicles. An optional remote interface links transmitters to regulatory and commercial users in real-time. A microprocessor in the receiver uses the coded signals to produce messages from prerecorded messages or from message parts stored in a replaceable memory device, and to provide the messages either audibly, visually or both. The microprocessor functions under operator supplied instructions to select certain message types for display and to reject unwanted messages. The memory device is recorded in one or more languages to allow the operator to select a preferred language for message presentation.

column12: Métodos para configurar uma unidade de controle para operar com um dispositivo a ser controlado e para controlar dispositivos controlados eletronicamente por uma unidade de controle, e, sistema de controle
column13: "MéTODOS PARA CONFIGURAR UMA UNIDADE DE CONTROLE PARA OPERAR COM UM DISPOSITIVO A SER CONTROLADO E PARA CONTROLAR DISPOSITIVOS CONTROLADOS ELETRONICAMENTE POR UMA UNIDADE DE CONTROLE, E, SISTEMA DE CONTROLE". Métodos e sistemas são descritos para a configuração de um controle remoto universal para operação com um sistema possuindo dispositivos a serem controlados tais como uma TV, VCR, aparelhos eletrónicos, onde os dispositivos são preferivelmente interconectados. Um método inclui as etapas de se fazer com que os dispositivos a serem controlados forneçam uma listagem das capacidades de cada dispositivo, reconhecendo um único conjunto de indicadores de característica abstrata padrão; processamento dos ditos indicadores; e, mapeamento dos ditos indicadores em códigos IR específicos e teclas de acordo com a dita lista de capacidades do dito dispositivo controlado. Uma modalidade é otimizada para uso com um controle remoto virtual, onde apenas os ícones que correspondem às capacidades relacionadas são exibidas em uma tela de toque do controle remoto virtual. Tal modalidade é particularmente bem adequada para o controle de diferentes famílias da capacidade de função associada com diferentes dispositivos de entretenimento correspondentes para alcançar um entretenimento integrado, ou tarefa, agrupamento. A redução dos ícones exibidos para o usuário de forma forçosa reduz a complexidade aparente do remoto com o qual os dispositivos são controlados.

column12: Dynamic image adjustment to enhance off- axis viewing in a display assembly
column13: A display assembly includes a display console displaying at least one image on an image plane. The image is divided into a plurality of pixels. A controller is operatively connected to the display console and includes a processor and tangible, non-transitory memory on which is recorded instructions for executing a method for dynamically adjusting the image in real-time for off-axis viewing. The controller is programmed to generate a compensation-over-viewing-angle map which includes respective compensation factors for each of the plurality of pixels for multiple viewing positions. In one embodiment, the controller is programmed to apply separate respective compensation factors for the instantaneous viewing positions of a first user at a time j and a second user at a time k. In another embodiment, the controller is programmed to apply first and second compensation factors simultaneously at a time m, for a first image and a second image, respectively.

column12: Process for the Hydrogenation of Coal
column13: 1,154,322. Coking coal. GAS COUNCIL. 6 Oct., 1967 [6 Oct., 1966], No. 44733/66. Heading C5E. Methane - containing gas is made by introducing powdered raw coal into a recycling bed of non-coking material at 600‹ to 1000‹ C. fluidized by an hydrogenating gas suitably at a pressure of 10 to 200 atmos., the rate of introduction of the coal into the bed being such that the coal is rapidly heated, at least partially hydrogenated, and converted to a non- coking condition. The residue of non-coking powdered char may be subsequently hydrogenated under more severe conditions to produce more methane and a residue which may be used for hydrogen manufacture. Inside the cylindrical reaction vessel 3 is a cylinder 4 mounted coaxially and spaced from a shorter cylinder 5 by a gap 6. The fluidized solids are caused to circulate up the cylinder 4 and down the annulus between 3 and 4 by passing most of the hydrogen through the pipe 10 into the chamber 7 and thence into the central tube 4. A smaller amount of hydrogen is passed through the pipe 11 to fluidize the descending solid particles. To start the process the bed is formed from a non- coking fluidizable solid, e.g. high or medium temperature coke, which is gradually displaced as the bed is continuously withdrawn through pipe 14 while powdered coal is fed to the bed, through pipe 12, entrained in gas. Both the coal and the hydrogen may be preheated. Additional heat may be obtained by simultaneously carrying out other reactions in the bed, e.g. an oxygen containing gas may be added or a light petroleum distillate can be fed and hydrogenated.

column12: IMPREGNATED BRUSH APPLICATOR FOR MEDICAL ADHESIVES AND SEALANTS
column13: High viscosity medical adhesive formulations are provided with an applicator device that allows the medical adhesives to be easily sterilized, accurately dispensed and optimally cured for medical applications. The preferred medical adhesive formulations include 2-octyl cyanoacrylate and n-butyl-2-cyanoacrylate monomers in formulation with various additives. The medical adhesive can be formulated to be bio-absorbable and/or bio-degradable. Suitable thickeners, stabilizers, plasticizing agents, preservatives, reinforcing agents, colorants and anti-bacterial compounds may advantageously be included in the formulation. The formulation is preferably placed within a sealed aluminum or plastic tube. An applicator tip with plastic brush bristles is used for application and curing of the formulation. On one end, the applicator tip preferably has a cutting or piercing mechanism which is capable of breaking the seal on the tube. On the other end, the applicator tip brush bristles are coated and/or impregnated with a dry, solvent-free cyanoacrylate polymerization initiator and/or accelerator.

column12: Dynamische Bildanpassung zur Verbesserung der ausseraxialen Betrachtung in einer Anzeigeanordnung
column13: Eine Anzeigenanordnung beinhaltet eine Anzeigekonsole, die mindestens ein Bild auf einer Bildebene anzeigt. Das Bild ist in eine Vielzahl von Pixeln unterteilt. Ein Steuerung ist operativ mit der Anzeigekonsole verbunden und beinhaltet einen Prozessor und einen greifbaren, nichtflüchtigen Speicher, auf dem Anweisungen für die Ausführung eines Verfahrens zum dynamischen Einstellen des Bildes in Echtzeit für die außeraxiale Betrachtung aufgezeichnet sind. Die Steuerung programmiert ist, um eine Kompensation-over-Betrachtungswinkel-Karte zu erzeugen, die jeweilige Kompensationsfaktoren für jedes der Vielzahl von Pixeln für mehrere Betrachtungspositionen beinhaltet. In einer Ausführungsform ist die Steuerung so programmiert, dass sie jeweils getrennte Kompensationsfaktoren für die momentanen Betrachtungspositionen eines ersten Benutzers zu einem Zeitpunkt j und einem zweiten Benutzer zu einem Zeitpunkt k anwendet. In einer anderen Ausführungsform ist die Steuerung so programmiert, dass sie gleichzeitig eine erste und eine zweite Kompensationsfaktor zu einem Zeitpunkt m, für ein erstes Bild und ein zweites Bild anwendet.

column12: AIRCRAFT AIRCREW LIFE SUPPORT APPARATUS
column13: A breathing demand regulator for use in aircrew life support apparatus has an aneroid capsule 56 coacting with a valve head 50 to restrict outflow from a breathing pressure control chamber 32. The aneroid capsule expands t.o move the valve head in the event of aircraft cabin altitude rising above a predetermined level due to loss of cabin pressure. An end face 53 of a valve stem 51 supporting the valve head senses inflation pressure of an aircrew G-suit by way of a passageway 59 for movement of the valve head in the presence of G-load. This arrangement provides for increased control pressure and, hence, increased breathing gas pressure in a regulator outlet 13, in meeting the higher of requirements for positive pressure breathing to protect an aircrew member exposed to both G-load and high aircraft ambient altitude (say above 12000 metres). The regulator is disclosed in combination with an anti-G valve arrangement 90, 100 and a G-suit inflation control valve arrangement 60, 61 and 120, 121 that provides the higher of G-suit inflation pressure requirement for protecting the aircrew member when exposed to high aircraft ambient altitude in the presence of G-load.

column12: Real-time quality control during manufacturing using augmented reality
column13: Various techniques are described herein that provide for real-time quality control during manufacturing using augmented reality. In particular, in one embodiment, techniques herein project a three-dimensional (3D) virtual shape/model onto a work-in-progress part in the real-world in order to see defects in real-time, thus allowing for mid-manufacturing corrections. The embodiments herein generally consist of first calibrating a “virtual world” to the real world, then calibrating the physical product to the virtual world, and lastly projecting information onto the physical product, such as various design information and/or quality control information.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR STORING AND RETRIEVING A TRUSTED SECURE DATA OBJECT BY AND AMONG MULTIPLE PARTIES
column13: The system may perform a method for controlling access to a secure data object. The secure data object may be a tax return. The method may implement a distributed ledger and tokens. A tax preparer or an owner of a tax return may put the tax return into a distributed ledger and securely associate the tax return with a token. By sharing the token with authorized third parties, the tax preparer or owner of the tax return may allow others to access the tax return. By retrieving the tax return from the distributed ledger with the token, rather than receiving the tax return directly from an owner of the tax return, the authorized third parties may be assured of the authenticity of the tax return that they are accessing with the token.

column12: METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR MONITORING AND DIAGNOSING SYSTEM PERFORMANCE.
column13: Procédé et appareil permettant de contrôler et de diagnostiquer le fonctionnement d'un système, consistant à acquérir des données du système en cours d'essai et à les comparer à un modèle d'événements. Le modèle d'événements comprend une base de données ayant des enregistrements d'événements qui définissent à l'avance des événements pouvant se produire dans le fonctionnement du système. Chaque enregistrement d'événements comprend une dépendance vectorielle d'état qui établit une liste des événements qui doivent avoir lieu avant l'événement pré-défini et un ou plusieurs paramètres critiques définissant les données qui doivent se produire pendant le fonctionnement du système pour l'événement ayant eu lieu. La reconnaissance des événements est effectuée en comparant chaque enregistrement d'événements avec les données acquises de fonctionnement et avec des événements déjà reconnus. A chaque enregistrement d'événements dans la base de données est associée une action d'acquisition de données intelligentes qui définit une action ou décision à prendre suite à la reconnaissance de l'enregistrement d'événements. Ces actions peuvent modifier le fonctionnement du système contrôlé ou l'acquisition des données. De plus, les résultats de la reconnaissance d'événements peuvent être analysés dans un ordinateur.

column12: REAL-TIME QUALITY CONTROL DURING MANUFACTURING USING AUGMENTED REALITY
column13: Various techniques are described herein that provide for real-time quality control during manufacturing using augmented reality. In particular, in one embodiment, techniques herein project a three-dimensional (3D) virtual shape/model onto a work-in-progress part in the real-world in order to see defects in real-time, thus allowing for mid-manufacturing corrections. The embodiments herein generally consist of first calibrating a “virtual world” to the real world, then calibrating the physical product to the virtual world, and lastly projecting information onto the physical product, such as various design information and/or quality control information.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR SELECTING A TAX RETURN FROM MULTIPLE TAX RETURN PROCESSORS
column13: The system automatically selects an output data structure from among more than one output data structure generated by separate processors. For instance, the output data structures may have different performance scores, and the system and method may compute difference scores to compare the independently determined performance scores of the output data structures. Depending on the magnitude of the difference score, the output data structures can be determined to be valid or to be invalid so that further processing is performed to generate a valid output data structure. In some instances, the data structures are tax returns, and the system automatically computes a tax return, and the comparing process advantageously yields a tax return that optimizes a tax filing strategy.

column12: DYNAMIC IMAGE ADJUSTMENT TO ENHANCE OFF- AXIS VIEWING IN A DISPLAY ASSEMBLY
column13: A display assembly includes a display console displaying at least one image on an image plane. The image is divided into a plurality of pixels. A controller is operatively connected to the display console and includes a processor and tangible, non-transitory memory on which is recorded instructions for executing a method for dynamically adjusting the image in real-time for off-axis viewing. The controller is programmed to generate a compensation-over-viewing-angle map which includes respective compensation factors for each of the plurality of pixels for multiple viewing positions. In one embodiment, the controller is programmed to apply separate respective compensation factors for the instantaneous viewing positions of a first user at a time j and a second user at a time k. column12: PROCEDE DE REGULATION DE LA PRESSION DE GONFLAGE D'UN VETEMENT DE PROTECTION ANTI-G POUR HOMME D'EQUIPAGE D'UN AVION ET EQUIPEMENT DE VIE POUR CE DERNIER.
column13: Ce procédé consiste à mettre en mémoire, dans un ordinateur embarqué, des variations programmées de pression de gonflage de combinaison anti-g en fonction soit de l'augmentation d'accélération, soit de la diminution de pression de cabine, à introduire dans l'ordinateur des signaux représentatifs de l'accélération et de la pression de cabine, à consulter les variations programmées et présenter les valeurs requises pour la pression de gonflage, à déterminer la valeur la plus élevée de celle-ci correspondant à des signaux simultanés d'accélération et de pression de cabine exigeant un gonflage, à produire un signal de demande de pression de gonflage et à le transmettre à une unité spécialement affectée à la commande d'une soupape de commande de gonflage; à capter la pression dans la combinaison anti-g, à envoyer en réaction à ladite unité un signal représentatif de cette pression et à le comparer au signal de demande de pression, à produire un signal d'erreur compensé et à le combiner au signal de demande de façon à fournir un signal de demande d'asservissement et à transmettre ce signal à une soupape de servocommandes afin de réaliser la régulation d'une pression d'asservissement qui sert à déplacer une soupape de fourniture de gaz de gonflage vers l'ouverture et une soupape de mise à l'air vers la fermeture.

column12: Aircraft aircrew life support systems
column13: Inflation pressure of an aircrew G-suit is controlled by an aircraft systems computer 120 sending a pressure demand signal PDEM to a dedicated electronic control unit (ECU) 123 to operate a pressure servo loop 124-129. The computer 120 stores schedules of G-suit inflation pressure against increasing acceleration Gz and decreasing cabin ambient pressure PAMB and outputs the higher to the ECO. The ECU compares an existing G-suit inflation pressure P0 signal with the inflation pressure demand signal and generates a compensated error signal which is combined with the inflation pressure demand signal to provide the servodemand signal. Servo-pressure is regulated by a torque motor controlled valve 124, 125 which receives a servo-demand signal from the ECU 123 and controls movement of inflation gas supply and vent valves 126 and 127, respectively. The use of the ECU for the computationally intensive control task optimises the use of the aircraft systems computer. A combined breathing demand regulator and G-suit inflation pressure control valve which continues to function in the absence of electrical power after bail-out from an aircraft is also disclosed. <IMAGE>

column12: METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR MONITORING AND DIAGNOSING SYSTEM PERFORMANCE
column13: Method and apparatus for performing system monitoring and diagnostics is disclosed. In performing system monitoring, data is acquired from the system under test and compared to an event model. The event model comprises a database having event records which pre-define events which can occur the system's performance. Each event record includes a state vector dependency which lists the events which must occur prior to the pre-defined event occurring and one or more critical parameters defining the data which must occur during the system's performance for the event to have occurred. Event recognition is performed by comparing each event record to acquired operational data and to events already recognized. Associated with each event record in the database is an intelligent data acquisition action which defines an action to be taken as a result of the event record being recognized. These actions can modify the performance of the system being monitored or the acquisition of data. Additionally, the results of the event recognition step can be further analyzed in a computer.

column12: SYSTEM UND VERFAHREN ZUR AUFRÜSTUNG DER FERNSTEUERFUNKTIONALITÄT EINER EINRICHTUNG
column13: A system and method for upgrading remote control application resident on a device. To this end, a markup language file is created. The markup language file has a representation of information used to setup the remote control application to communicate with an appliance. The markup language file may be executed, on the device or an intermediate client with which the device is synchronized, to upload the representation of the information to a remote server. At the remote server, the uploaded information is used to automatically display user-selectable, downloadable data files relevant to the control of the appliance. Downloaded data files, which may include command codes and/or graphical user interface elements, may be used within the device to upgrade the ability of the remote control application to communicate with the appliance. The information uploaded to the server may also be used to generate demographic data regarding consumer preferences.

column12: DIGITAL INTERCONNECTION OF ELECTRONICS ENTERTAINMENT EQUIPMENT
column13: Methods and systems are disclosed for setting up a universal remote control for operation with a system having devices to be controlled such as a TV, VCR, electronics appliances, wherein the devices are preferably interconnected. One method includes the steps of having the devices to be controlled provide a listing of the capabilities of each device, recognizing a single set of standard abstract feature indicators; processing said indicators; and, mapping said indicators into specific IR codes and keys according to said list of capabilities of said controlled device. One embodiment is optimized for use with a virtual remote control, wherein only icons corresponding to related capabilities is displayed on a touch screen of the virtual remote control. Such an embodiment is particularly well suited for controlling different families of function capability associated with correspondingly different entertainment devices to achieve an integrated entertainment, or task, grouping. Reduction of the icons displayed to the user perforce reduces the apparent complexity of the remote with which the devices are controlled.

column12: THREE-DIMENSIONAL IMAGE SOURCE FOR ENHANCED PEPPER'S GHOST ILLUSION
column13: Systems and methods herein are directed to three-dimensional image sources for an enhanced Pepper's Ghost Illusion. In one embodiment, a contoured bounce is described, allowing for contorting a bounce to different shapes, giving it enhanced three-dimensional (3D) effect. For instance, the bounce may include certain topography (raised portions), or else may actually comprise various 3D shapes (e.g., cubes, semi-spheres, etc.). In another embodiment, a multi-level image source is described, allowing for multiple image sources (e.g., projected bounces and/or panel displays) to be used and placed at different heights with respect to a transparent viewing screen, thus projecting images that appear at various depths, increasing the three-dimensional (3D) effect of the Pepper's Ghost Illusion. In addition, in one embodiment, the heights of the image sources may be adjusted (e.g., dynamically), making corresponding holographic images change their depth perspective to an audience, further enhancing the 3D effect.

column12: BREATHABLE GAS DELIVERY REGULATOR
column13: A breathable gas delivery regulator (10) has a demand valve (15) which will open easily to substantially consistent efforts of a user throughout the pressure range of supply gas from a molecular sieve oxygen generator (not shown). The demand valve (15) is balanced by supply gas pressure and is operably connected, such as by a mechanical lever (29), with a pressure-responsive wall (27) of a demand-pressure sensing chamber (12) which is in fluid communication with a gas delivery outlet (17). Movements of the pressure-responsive wall (27) cause the demand valve (15) to move towards opening or closing and thereby regulate the flow of supply gas from a supply gas inlet (16) to the gas delivery outlet (17).
